occurrenceRemarks: Vi gikk en tur mellom Søndre Spro og Gaupemyrdammen i Nesodden kommune, på formiddagen første nyttårsdag. Vi går på stien gjennom skogen og må passere en stri bekk som det er laget en trebro over. Vi går ofte denne turen. I dag stoppet vi opp siden det hadde snødd et par timer tidligere og det var spor etter hund eller ulv i snøen over broen. Siden det ikke var spor etter mennesker, og kun dyrespor i en retning og sporene var forholdsvis store - ca 10cm tok vi noen bilder som vi håper kan gi svar på om det har vært ulv i området, eller bare en stor hund som har gått i skogen alene.
name: Canis lupus Linnaeus, 1758

occurrenceRemarks: I've never heard Coyotes sound like these; they were somehow clearer in life than on recording. Help with ID would be appreciated
identificationRemarks: Hi Steve--the coyotes I hear in central Sioux County when I overnight there sound pretty similar to much of your recording. It's truly amazing the range of calls/vocalizations they can make. What was even more surprising (to me anyway) was how few coyotes--or even a single individual--can create what sounds like many more. It wasn't until I was able to observe some specific individuals calling that I discovered this; otherwise I would have continued assuming the chorus was being made by several of them. Being in or near draws/hilly areas/embankments can also amplify and otherwise distort the sounds too, making it even more difficult to determine direction of the coyote/call, etc. I think many peoples' perceptions of coyote ""numbers"" in a specific location may well be skewed by how some specific coyotes vocalize.
name: Canis latrans Say, 1823
